qx|13B06,RUFFING POWER IS CONFINED TO THE DUMMY|
HT|d|Va|2|CP|4|CS|1|AT|^-
{    RUFFING POWER IS CONFINED TO THE DUMMY    }
^-|CS||CP||fp||AT|^B@2^Y@3I|FP||AT|n all the example deals in this chapter, you may have noticed that ruffing power appeared only in the Dummy's hand, never in the Declarer's hand. Though it may seem incredible, there is practically no such thing as a ruffing-trick to be found in the long trump hand, which is almost always the Declarer's hand. |
PG| ***** 131 ***** |


cp|8|at|

^*iSam Fry, Jr.:|cp||at| In those rare cases where the Dummy contains the greater length in trumps, the play is simply reversed^*N.
|
PG| ***** 132 ***** |


AT|
The reason for this may be quickly explained. If the hand containing the greater number of trumps wishes to take tricks with them, he needs only to establish the trump suit. If he holds five trumps to the Ace-King, and his Partner holds four small ones, two rounds of the suit will probably catch all the adverse trumps, and the three trumps he has left in his own hand will all be high. |
PG| ***** 133 ***** |


AT|If now he leads some card from the Dummy and plays a trump on it from his hand, he is not making a ruffing-trick—he is, as a matter of fact, not gaining a trick at all. He could easily have accomplished the same result by leading the trump from his hand and discarding the card (which he led) from the Dummy. |
PG| ***** 134 ***** |


AT|

The high trumps in his own hand are good no matter how he plays them. Put this way, |cp|8|at|the lead of trumps for no reason at all, you see, gains nothing. Properly speaking, a ruffing-trick is a trump trick which cannot be made by leading trumps; it is always an extra trick, never an automatic trick.|cp||at||
PG| ***** 135 ***** |


AT|

This fact—|cp|8|at|that ruffing power is generally confined to the Dummy|cp||at|—is of importance because it crops up frequently in defensive play. It is a common failing among average players to take tricks quickly, as Declarers, with tricks in their own hands. Most of the time they do not realize that they are reducing their strength and weakening their position. |FP|2|
pg| ***** 136 ***** |


cp|8|at|The Declarer who takes out his own trumps immediately, under the delusion that he is making ruffing-tricks, is merely taking a few tricks early in the play with cards which he should be reserving as controls against later attacks.|cp||FP|
|
