{        Unnecessary ruffs        }
^-|CS||CP||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|At the end of the chapter, Watson talks about unnecessary ruffs. This is a common mistake that I see many less experienced players make. If, as declarer, you are out of a suit, but dummy still has cards remaining in that suit, there is no reason to ruff those cards out in your hand. In fact, as Watson points out, entering dummy so that you can lead a card to trump in your hand is no different than leading out a trump and discarding that card from dummy. |
PG| ***** 143 ***** |


AT|

And, there is sometimes a disadvantage in doing that, as it shortens your trumps, and may, in fact, make you run out of trumps prematurely, allowing the defenders to cash low cards that you otherwise would have been able to trump. If you have a good reason to do so, such as needing an entry to your hand, then you might want to ruff one of dummy's losers. Otherwise, it is bad technique to unnecessarily ruff dummy's low cards. |
PG| ***** 144 ***** |


AT|

By the way, this illustrates an important point about choice of contracts. In general, it is better to play in a 4-4 fit than a 5-3 fit. This is because you can use the 5 card suit to pitch losers from the other hand, and trump those losers. However, if you are in danger of losing control, then the presence of a 5th trump in one hand gives you an extra measure of protection. This should be given serious consideration when choosing your contract, particularly if you have a singleton or void in a side suit; in that case, having a long trump suit can be crucial in preventing you from losing control.|
PG| ***** 145 ***** |


cp|8|AT|^B@2

^*BMovie Maker: ^*N|cp||at|We updated this presentation in May 2011. Aggie, did the second editing and based on her findings and with Howard's permission we decided to add his latest opinion on the subject which you can read next.|
PG| ***** 146 ***** |


AT|^*I 

"Having said all that, which most experts teach, I would like to alert you that it is safer to play in a 5-3 fit than a 4-4 fit. That is because almost 1/3 of the time, trumps do not break 3-2. If, for example, they break 4-1, then in a 4-4 fit one defender has as many trumps as you do. In a 5-3 fit, you still have more trumps. So, assuming you don't need the extra trick that a 4-4 fit sometimes yields, the 5-3 fit is better."^*N|
