{    Counting Trump Tricks    }
^-|CS||CP||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Here is the method I use to count trump tricks. I count the number of trump tricks I have in the hand that has longer trumps. I then add to that the number of ruffs I will get in the other hand. |
PG| ***** 148 ***** |


AT|

Let me give a couple of examples. Suppose you hold AQ1086 opposite KJ97. You will score 5 trumps in your own hand. If dummy is out of a suit, and you can ruff in dummy twice, you will also score 2 ruffs in dummy. So the total number of trump tricks you will take is 7, the 5 trumps in your hand plus the 2 ruffs in dummy.    |
PG| ***** 149 ***** |


AT|

As another example, suppose you have KQJ109 opposite 543 and you only have the opportunity to ruff once in dummy. Your total number of trump tricks is 5, 4 in your hand (you have to lose the Ace) plus one ruff in dummy.	|
PG| ***** 150 ***** |


AT|

There is one slightly tricky situation which occurs on rare occasions. Let us look at the first example again, AQ1086 opposite KJ97. Suppose dummy is 4-3-3-3, so you cannot ruff anything in dummy. Well, then you might think you will only score 5 trump tricks. However, assume you have a void in a suit and dummy has 2 low cards in that suit. If you ruff both low cards in your hand, you will be reduced to 3 trumps and dummy will still have four. So, using my method for counting trump tricks, you have six trump tricks -- the 4 trump tricks in the "long" hand (dummy) plus the 2 ruffs in your hand.
|
